</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFAF6A10FA54914F1819BC6C" pageId="84" pageNumber="842" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFAF6A10FA54914F1819BC6C" blockId="84.[1447,2656,1227,2281]" pageId="84" pageNumber="842">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFAF6A10FA54914F182FBC05" bold="true" box="[1448,1583,1814,1847]" pageId="84" pageNumber="842">Breeding.</emphasis>
A lactating Thomas’s Big-eared Brown Bat was caught in November in 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFAF6A10F5CF914F1815BC6C" name="Argentina" pageId="84" pageNumber="842">Argentina</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFAF6A10FA5B913C164FBCCE" pageId="84" pageNumber="842" type="activity">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFAF6A10FA5B913C164FBCCE" blockId="84.[1447,2656,1227,2281]" pageId="84" pageNumber="842">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFAF6A10FA5B913C1897BCB4" bold="true" box="[1447,1687,1893,1926]" pageId="84" pageNumber="842">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Roosts of Thomas's Big-eared Brown Bats were found in a wooded storage barn. Echolocation calls have QCF components. Calls sweep down from c.38 kHz to ¢.26 kHz, with duration of c.1-3 milliseconds. Interpulse interval averages 94 milliseconds, and peak frequency is ¢.30 kHz.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFAF6A10FA5B9E5A1753B316" box="[1447,2387,2051,2084]" pageId="84" pageNumber="842" type="biology_ecology">
